# Next steps — {{PROJECT_NAME}}

This is the human handoff memo for {{PROJECT_NAME}}, the shareable companion to the `ROADMAP.md` checklist. Read it to learn what was just built, what to do next, and who owns it, without opening a tracker or a board. The assignable, checkbox version of everything below lives in `ROADMAP.md`; this page exists so a PI or stakeholder can stay oriented in a couple of minutes.

We scaffolded {{PROJECT_NAME}} at level **{{LEVEL}}**, deliberately right-sized to the team and horizon that exist now rather than to a project we imagine later. What that gives you is ready to use today: the repository structure, the documentation, and the level's working artifacts are in place, so you can clone the repo, find your way around from the `README.md`, and start working against real data. Building only this much now — and recording the rest as deferred work — is the intended workflow, not a corner cut.

The top next actions, and who owns them, are tracked as an assignable checklist in `ROADMAP.md` under "This level's work"; treat that table as the live to-do list and check items off as their definition-of-done is met. Default ownership sits with **{{OWNER_DEFAULT}}** unless a row names someone else, so reassign rows there rather than tracking owners in your head, which keeps a single place to answer "who is doing what." The short version for a reader who will not open the table: finish the level's core artifacts (for example, fill the data dictionary before ingesting and complete the responsible-data checklist before sharing), then hand the rest forward.

A few items are marked **blocking** in `ROADMAP.md`, and they gate real actions — ingesting sensitive data, publishing, or climbing to the next level — so resolve them, or explicitly accept the risk in writing, before doing the thing they guard. <!-- IF:SENSITIVE -->This project handles **{{SENSITIVITY_TIER}}** data, so the governance, access-tier, and remedy items are blocking by design: an identifier scheme or a retained record without the duties that constrain it is theater, and must not ship before those duties do.<!-- /IF -->Do not route around a blocking item quietly; raising it here is how a stakeholder learns the project is paused for a good reason.

To climb to the next level, re-run the `data-project` skill in this directory and ask for the next rung (for example, "take this to the next level"); it adds only the new level's artifacts, refreshes `ROADMAP.md`, and leaves what already works untouched. Climbing is how scope grows on purpose instead of by accident, so prefer it to hand-adding heavyweight structure this level does not yet need.

